                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d590">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4660: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Switzerland (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1" type="to"
                            >Wilson</persName>), at Geneva</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-10T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 10, 1932—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>40. Your 67, March 9, 8 p.m. Dr. <persName corresp="#p_YH2">Yen</persName>’s
                    letter was unauthorized and inaccurate. I expressed no opinion to <persName
                        corresp="#p_YH2">Hawkling Yen</persName> and have formulated no plan as to
                    the maintenance of order in the occupied area at the withdrawal of the Japanese
                    troops. This seems to me a matter to be discussed at the conference to be held
                    in Shanghai in pursuance of the Assembly resolution. So far as I know, no one
                    has as yet undertaken to specify what the arrangements must be. You may inform
                    any responsible inquirer of the facts and my views as above.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
